# shellcheck configuration -- read by BOTH the local `shellcheck` invocation and
# CI's reviewdog/action-shellcheck, so the two run the same rules and a script
# that is clean locally is clean in CI. (Same local/CI parity principle as the
# markdownlint pin -- see #2500.)
#
# Why these are disabled:
#
# SC2001 -- "See if you can use ${variable//search/replace} instead."
#   The suggestion does not apply to this codebase's actual usage. Every hit is
#   of the form:
#
#       echo "$MULTILINE_VAR" | sed 's/^/  /'
#
#   i.e. indent EVERY LINE of a multi-line string. Bash parameter expansion
#   operates on the string as a whole and has no per-line `^` anchor, so it
#   cannot express this. Rewriting to ${var//.../...} would silently change the
#   output. The rule is style-only and its advice is wrong here.
#
# SC1091 -- "Not following: <file> was not specified as input."
#   Sourced helpers (e.g. scripts/lib/run-paths.sh) are resolved at runtime from
#   the repo root. shellcheck cannot follow them when linting a file in
#   isolation, which is how both CI and the pre-commit hook invoke it. This is a
#   limitation of the linter's file-at-a-time mode, not a defect in the script.
#
# Both are informational severities. They are disabled rather than raised to a
# higher severity because reviewdog concludes `failure` on findings of ANY level
# despite `fail_level: error`, so a purely stylistic notice was turning the
# Shellcheck check red on any PR that touched a shell script -- while the same
# script passed locally.
disable=SC2001
disable=SC1091
